                  fitted with generalized estimating equations were used to
                  determine which social, housing, management, life history, and
                  demographic variables were associated with daytime and
                  nighttime stereotypic behavior rates. Species was a
                  significant risk factor in both models, with Asian elephants
                  at greater risk (daytime: p<0.001, Risk Ratio = 4.087;
                  nighttime: p<0.001, Risk Ratio = 8.015). For both species,
                  spending time housed separately (p<0.001, Risk Ratio = 1.009),
                  and having experienced inter-zoo transfers (p<0.001, Risk
                  Ratio = 1.175), increased the risk of performing higher rates
                  of stereotypy during the day, while spending more time with
                  juvenile elephants (p<0.001, Risk Ratio = 0.985), and engaging
                  with zoo staff reduced this risk (p = 0.018, Risk Ratio =
                  0.988). At night, spending more time in environments with both
                  indoor and outdoor areas (p = 0.013, Risk Ratio = 0.987) and
                  in larger social groups (p = 0.039, Risk Ratio = 0.752)
                  corresponded with reduced risk of performing higher rates of
                  stereotypy, while having experienced inter-zoo transfers (p =
                  0.033, Risk Ratio = 1.115) increased this risk. Overall, our
                  results indicate that factors related to the social
                  environment are most influential in predicting elephant
